<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palestinian-Israeli Talks Resume in Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Palestinian-Israeli Talks Resume in Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    'Abd-Rabbuh: Talks in `Death Throes' </H4>

<F P=102> NC1004063994 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 0500 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1004063994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Palestinian-Israeli talks on the implementation 
of the Gaza-Jericho agreement will resume in Cairo today. The 
Palestinian side will be chaired by Dr. Nabil Sha'th, 
Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat's political adviser. The 
Israeli side will be chaired by General Amnon Shahaq, Israeli 
deputy chief of staff. 
  Shim'on Peres stated that there is a great possibility of 
completing the Israeli withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho at the 
end of the current month. Peres said in an interview with the 
Qatari newspaper AL-SHARQ that the forces of the Israeli army 
have started withdrawing from the autonomy area. 
  Last night, Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa held a meeting with 
PLO Executive Committee member Mahmud 'Abbas. 
  The foreign minister stated after the meeting that the 
meeting is part of the framework of the continuing 
Palestinian-Egyptian coordination in the peace process. He said 
that they discussed the current stage of the peace talks, which 
will resume this morning. He said this new round of talks will 
continue for two or three days, after which the two sides will 
be able to set the date for starting implementation of the 
Declaration of Principles. 
  PLO Executive Committee member Yasir 'Abd-Rabbuh stated 
yesterday that the Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of Principles 
is in its death throes. 'Abd-Rabbuh demanded that immediate 
talks should be started on the final position of all the 
occupied territories. He said that autonomy talks with Israel 
cannot continue because it wants total hegemony over the 
Palestinian police force in the occupied territories. 

</TEXT>

