<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Secretary on Nuclear Talks With Talbott </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Secretary on Nuclear Talks With Talbott </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1004083994 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service in 
English 0800 GMT 10 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1004083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The U.S. deputy secretary of state, Mr. Strobe 
Talbott, said that his visit to Pakistan was most productive and 
useful. The United States shares with Pakistan the objective of 
nuclear nonproliferation in South Asian region. Talking to 
newsmen at Chaklala base before his departure for Europe, Mr. 
Talbott said Pakistan and the United States would pursue their 
approach toward nonproliferation in South Asian region and on a 
variety of subjects. He made it clear that the U.S. approach to 
nonproliferation was multidimensional. He said he has a great 
degree of optimism for achieving concrete results in the future 
that will serve the security and political interests of Pakistan. 
  The foreign secretary, Mr. Najmuddin Sheikh, said there was 
no question of an agreement on nuclear nonproliferation, but 
discussions will continue in order to arrive at a mutually 
agreed approach. He said the two sides agreed that there should 
be capping, reduction, and elimination of nuclear weapons from 
South Asia as well as weapons of mass destruction. The foreign 
secretary said Pakistan explained its stand and position on the 
nuclear issue and Mr. Talbott certainly has a much clearer 
understanding of Pakistan's position. 

</TEXT>

