<H3> <TI>   Says Settlements To Remain </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Says Settlements To Remain </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1104052794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 0400 GMT 11 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1104052794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin says getting out of 
the Gaza Strip will bring only good things to Israel. 
Addressing a dinner of the Israel Bonds in Tel Aviv last night, 
the prime minister added that the Gaza settlement of Netzarim, 
despite the fact that only 27 families live there, will remain 
in place, as will all other settlements in the territories. 
This government, declared the prime minister, will continue the 
peace process even if it only has a majority of one. 
  [Begin Rabin recording] We achieved in the agreement with 
the PLO what we could not achieve with anyone: that the unity 
of Jerusalem will not be under question for the interim period; 
that all the settlements will remain in place. Believe me, in 
Greater Gaza, in the Gaza Strip, there are three-quarters of a 
million Palestinians and less than 5,000 Israelis. Netzarim -- 
27 families in the outskirts of Greater Gaza of a quarter of a 
million people. 
  We'll continue. The present Government of Israel, regardless 
to domestic opposition, we are a democracy, and as long as we 
have got a majority in our elected legislative body, we will 
continue. Even if I have got a majority of one, I am determined 
to go on. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

