<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPLA Holds 1st Convention in 10 Years </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPLA Holds 1st Convention in 10 Years </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1104213394 Paris AFP in English 1730 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1104213394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, April 11 (AFP) -- Delegates of Sudan's 
southern rebel movement fighting the Khartoum government held 
their first conference since the group's creation in 1983, rebel 
sources said here Monday. 
  More than 500 delegates of the Sudan People's Liberation 
Army 
(SPLA) and its political wing, the Sudan People's Liberation 
Movement (SPLM), participated in the convention, which was held 
in southern Sudan and ended Friday, the sources said. 
  SPLA leader Colonel John Garang attended. 
  The conference was called in a bid to reinforce Garang's 
authority in the face of an internal power struggle with 
SPLA-United, a breakaway faction formed in 1991 and led by one 
of his former aides, Riek Machar. 
  The sources said the conference's resolutions would be 
published in the next few days. 
  They added that one of the meeting's objectives was to 
modify 
the SPLA charter, which stipulates that the rebels are fighting 
for a share of power within a united Sudan. 
  The movement has in recent years shifted towards a 
separatist 
stance favouring a division of Sudan into two independent states 
-- a Moslem north and a Christian south. 
  The SPLA and the Sudanese Government held brief and 
inconclusive talks last month in Nairobi within the framework of 
wider peace negotiations brokered by the regional 
Inter-Governmental Authority and Drought and Development, which 
comprises representatives from Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, and 
Uganda. 
  The negotiations are scheduled to resume mid-May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-12650 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes070_g_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-070 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Warring' Faction Refuses To Sign Treaty as Scheduled </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Warring' Faction Refuses To Sign Treaty as Scheduled </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA1004113694 Nairobi KBC Television Network in English 1800 
GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1004113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Nairobi KBC Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Negotiations involving Sudan's warring factions 
today hit a snag when one of the groups refused to be signatory 
to a treaty they were scheduled to endorse. 
  The treaty involves passing a decree to a free passage of 
relief food supplies and humanitarian assistance to the war 
affected areas in southern Sudan. Reliable sources at the 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs where negotiations are still going 
on, told KTN that two groups, the SPLA [Sudan People's 
Liberation Army] mainstream and Sudanese Government had agreed 
to sign the document but the other faction, SPLM [Sudan People's 
Liberation Movement] declined to be part of it. 
  SPLM alleged that there had been alterations in the treaty, 
thereby demanding that unless the alterations were removed they 
would not be signatories. The negotiations, which were chaired 
by the minister of research, science and applied technology, 
Zachary Onyonka, were also attended by United Nations Operation 
Lifeline Sudan representative and IGADD [Intergovernmental 
Authority on Drought and Development] representatives. By the 
time we went on air negotiations were still going on. 

</TEXT>

