<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abd-Rabbuh on Israeli Proposals, U.S. Stand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Abd-Rabbuh on Israeli Proposals, U.S. Stand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1104192794 London MBC Television in Arabic 1800 GMT 11 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1104192794 </F>
<F P=104>  London MBC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Yasir 'Abd-Rabbuh, head of the PLO </F>
Information Department, by Mufidah al-Hashani in Tunis; date not 
given -- recorded] 
  [Text] PLO Information Department Head Yasir 'Abd-Rabbuh 
has said the negotiations with Israel are being obstructed. He 
critized the U.S. position toward the faltering Middle East 
peace process. Mufidah al-Hashani interviewed 'Abd-Rabbuh in 
Tunis: 
  ['Abd-Rabbuh] The situation has actually resulted from the 
Israeli position, which offers proposals that try to regulate 
the occupation more than end the occupation of the Palestinian 
territories. The Israelis propose some ideas that aim to slice 
off parts of Gaza, especially in the coastal area and along the 
green line between the Gaza Strip and Israel. They also propose 
other ideas, greatly restricting and narrowing the powers of the 
Palestinian authorities and police. 
  [Al-Hashani] What is the new Palestinian proposal? 
  ['Abd-Rabbuh] What is now required is that the peace process 
be salvaged on a new basis and through a new approach; that is 
by the immediate transition to negotiations on the final stage. 
  [Al-Hashani] What is the current U.S. stand on the 
negotiations? 
  ['Abd-Rabbuh] So far we have not sensed a serious U.S. stand 
to affect the course of negotiations. The U.S. side merely 
presents proposals of a procedural and administrative nature. 

</TEXT>

