<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Blames Israel for Security Incidents </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Blames Israel for Security Incidents </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1204110394 Beirut Radio Lebanon in Arabic 0900 GMT 12 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1204110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Radio Lebanon </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In a statement to the magazine AL-AMN [Security] on 
security in Lebanon and Israel's role in the recent crimes 
committed because of its failure to make the peace talks 
succeed, Interior Minister Bisharah Mirhij has blamed Israel for 
the stumbling of the Middle East peace talks. He noted that 
given Israel's social and political structure and the aggressive 
and expansionist theory dominating its institutions, Israel 
finds it difficult to continue the peace process and ensure the 
conditions and concessions necessary for its success. He said 
that Israel's failure to instigate a civil war among the 
Palestinians prompted it to commit the crime of the al-Ibrahimi 
Mosque and then to attempt to disturb security and foment 
sedition in Lebanon, particularly with the horrific crime in the 
Sayyidat al-Najat Church in Zuq Mikha'il. He pointed out that 
there is a clear link between the two crimes at the al-Ibrahimi 
Mosque and Sayyidat al-Najat Church, with the aim of avoiding 
peace. 
  On the goal behind the recent security incidents, Mirhij 
said 
the perpetrators sought to harm the economic and social 
situation in Lebanon and to play on sensitivities to aggravate 
the situation and foil the formula that the Lebanese people 
agreed upon in al-Ta'if. 
  Asked about explosives being placed in Ghidras and the 
Lebanese Army surrounding the area, Mirhij attributed the 
security and political focus on the Kasrawan area to the bombing 
of the Sayyidat al-Najat Church and the French cultural center, 
which took place in that area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

