<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saddam's Adviser in Moscow To Discuss Oil Field Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saddam's Adviser in Moscow To Discuss Oil Field Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1104153794 Paris AFP in English 1424 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1104153794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nicosia, April 11 (AFP) -- An adviser to President 
Saddam Husayn has held talks in Moscow about Russia resuming 
work on developing a giant oil field in southern Iraq, a 
specialist newsletter reported here Monday. 
  'Adnan al-'Ani, an adviser with ministerial rank, led the 
delegation to Moscow last week to discuss developing the West 
al-Qurnah field when the UN embargo is lifted, the Middle East 
Economic Survey (MEES) said. 
  The field close to the northern tip of the North al-Rumaylah 
field will have an estimated output capacity of 600,000 barrels 
per day after a second phase of work is completed, it added. 
  In an agreement signed in April 1984, the former Soviet 
Union 
was to develop the field under an engineering, supply, and 
construction contract financed by a 2-billion dollar soft credit 
facility. 
  Technoexport, a Soviet firm, was responsible for the first 
phase with a production capacity of 200,000 bpd, according to 
MEES published in Cyprus. 
  Much of the field's surface facilities have been built, but 
Technoexport was behind schedule when Iraq in?nah field was 
discovered by the Iraqi National Oil Company in 1973. 
  A UN embargo was imposed on Iraq when it invaded Kuwait and 
the UN Security Council has set conditions for Iraq to meet in 
order to have the embargo lifted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

