<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wrapup of Reports on Visit of Iranian Parliamentary Speaker </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wrapup of Reports on Visit of Iranian Parliamentary Speaker </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Holds News Conference 12 Apr </H4>

<F P=102> LD1204110194 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0930 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1204110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Dear listeners, as you heard earlier, Mr. 
Nateq-Nuri, the Majles speaker, visited the 
Iran-Pakistan-Persian Research Center in Islamabad today and 
took part in a news conference in which he answered reporters' 
questions. Our correspondent reports: 
  [Correspondent] Mr. Nateq-Nuri described the results of his 
trip to this country as positive and said: Our discussions 
revealed that the two countries share the same viewpoints with 
respect to the issues of the world of Islam. In response to a 
question, the Majles speaker, who was speaking to 
correspondents, denied having any discussions with Pakistani 
authorities about cooperation on the manufacture and use of 
nuclear weapons. He said: We support the peaceful use of 
nuclear technology by Pakistan. 
  On the Kashmir issue, he said: The Islamic Republic of Iran 
can be a good mediator toward the resolution of this problem. 
He added: On the initiative of the Islamic Republic of Iran, it 
has been agreed that a delegation consisting of representatives 
of Islamic countries will be sent to study the situation in the 
part of Kashmir under the control of India and the members of 
this delegation have been selected. 
  Mr. Nateq-Nuri described Iran and Pakistan's capabilities 
for 
supplying one another's requirements as plentiful, saying: The 
Islamic Republic of Iran has agreed to increase the volume of 
gas exports to this country from 25,000 tonnes to 50,000 tonnes. 
  Elsewhere in the news conference, the Majles speaker 
explained that, with regard to Iran's three Persian Gulf islands 
[Abu Musa and the Lesser and Greater Tunbs], we are prepared to 
continue the contacts toward the resolution of the difficulties. 
  Mr. Nateq-Nuri also visited the Iran-Pakistan-Persian 
Research Center in Islamabad today. During the visit and in a 
gathering of dozens of Persian language lecturers in Pakistan, 
the Majles speaker called for the greatest possible efforts to 
be made to revive this language in Pakistan, and he described 
such efforts as very effective toward the protection of that 
country's cultural heritage. 

</TEXT>

