<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wrapup of Reports on Visit of Iranian Parliamentary Speaker </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wrapup of Reports on Visit of Iranian Parliamentary Speaker </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Condemns U.S. `Arrogance' </H4>

<F P=102> LD1204164894 Tehran IRNA in English 1504 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1204164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Islamabad, April 12, IRNA -- The speaker of Iran's 
parliament told a group of Pakistani Shiite and Sunni ulama here 
Tuesday that what has terrified global arrogance and the U.S. in 
particular today is the spread of Islamism in Muslim countries. 
  The speaker, Hojjat ol-Eslam 'Ali Akbar Nateq-Nuri also said 
the enemies of Islam were seriously concerned about the revival 
of Islamic movements in the remotest parts of the world and even 
in Europe. 
  He said the utterance of the word, Allah and the phrase 
Allaho Akbar (There is no god but Allah) is considered an 
offense by the global arrogance and that any body who abides by 
Islamic laws will be the target of U.S. propaganda ad military 
attacks. 
  "It is for this very reason that we now see enemies of Islam 
committing crimes against Muslims including women and children 
in every part of Islamic lands," he said. 
  Nateq-Nuri also warned that the U.S. was trying to prevent 
Muslims from getting united and engage them in internal problems 
in a bid to contain the spread of Islam. 
  "Muslims should seriously avoid discord, settle their 
differences by themselves and not allow foreigners to interfere 
in their internal affairs," he advised. 
  The unity between Shiites and Sunnis has been materialized 
in 
Iran for years, he said, adding "we appeal to world Muslims to 
follow the pattern of unity and sincerity between their Shiite 
and Sunni brothers in Iran." 
  Addressing Pakistani ulama, the Majlis speaker said the 
zealot Islamic groups who sow discord among Muslims are 
certainly against their interests. 

</TEXT>

