<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wrapup of Reports on Visit of Iranian Parliamentary Speaker </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wrapup of Reports on Visit of Iranian Parliamentary Speaker </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    2d Iranian Official Comments </H4>

<F P=102> LD1404103594 Tehran IRNA in English 0727 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1404103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lahore, April 14, IRNA -- A senior Majlis deputy 
said here Wednesday that the Islamic Iran would not stand the 
massacre of Muslims and pressures against them in any part of 
the world including Kashmir. Vice-Chairman of Majlis foreign 
policy commission Mohammad Javad Larijani who is currently 
accompanying Majlis Speaker 'Ali Akbar Nateq-Nuri in his tour of 
Pakistan, told IRNA that one of the valuable outcomes of 
Tehran-Islamabad talks was the speaker's proposal for the 
formation of ECO [Economic Cooperation Organization] 
inter-parliamentary group. 
  Representatives have been appointed by the two countries to 
follow up agreements reached between the two sides, Larijani 
noted, adding "we hope that the organization would be formed by 
the next year". Voicing Iran's readiness to cooperate in 
bringing an end to Kashmir problem, the Iranian parliamentarian 
called for negotiations between the belligerent parties to 
settle the dispute. The Islamic Republic of Iran believes that 
Kashmiri people should determine their own fate, Larijani 
remarked. 
  Underlining geopolitical and economic importance of the two 
countries, Larijani noted that with a total population of 200 
million and their access to different parts of Asia, specially 
the Indian Ocean, Gulf of Oman and the Persian Gulf, Iran and 
Pakistan, should be regarded as core for any regional 
arrangement, Larijani concluded. 

</TEXT>

