<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Possible Changes in U.S. Administration Assessed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Possible Changes in U.S. Administration Assessed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404125794 Tehran IRNA in English 1109 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1404125794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] London, Apr. 14, IRNA -- The American secretary of 
state, Warren Christopher, will resign by the end of this year 
and barring upsets, is expected to be replaced by his deputy, 
Strobe Talbott, say White House sources quoted by THE 
ECONOMIST's Foreign Report here. 
  U.S. foreign policy under Christopher was said to have been 
undynamic and a disappointment to the White House. The 
perception was that the previous republican administration would 
probably have been tougher and assertive if it remained in 
power. Foreign Report said that President Clinton had been 
unwillingly drawn into foreign policy issues instead of being 
allowed to concentrate on domestic affairs. 
  Some issues had been delegated to Vice President Al Gore 
rather than Christopher and more recently, the secretary of 
defense, Bill Perry, seemed to have been making the running on 
foreign policy. 
  Whether Talbott, the former Washington bureau chief of TIME 
magazine and long-standing friend of Clinton, makes American 
foreign policy, the weekly intelligence publication said, 
remained to be seen. 
  Although the deputy secretary of state knows Washington well 
and is a student of relations with Russia, he has held no 
personal experience of high office before. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

