<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saddam Reportedly `Confined to Bed' With `Serious' Illness </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saddam Reportedly `Confined to Bed' With `Serious' Illness </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1404115094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 14 Apr 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1404115094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Lebanon Arrests Two Iraqi Diplomats </F>
Following Assassination of Figure Opposed to Baghdad Government"] 
  [Excerpts] London, Beirut, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Lebanese 
security forces yesterday announced that an Iraqi oppositionist 
holding a Jordanian passport was shot dead the night before last 
in the area of 'Ayn al-Tinah in Beirut. 
  Lebanese security forces said that the murdered person is 
Talib Suhayl, an Iraqi oppositionist in exile who had lived in 
Lebanon for several years. [passage omitted] 
  In London, the "Free Iraqi Council" [FIC], an Iraqi 
opposition organization, has confirmed that Talib 'Ali Suhayl 
was a member of the council's Central Committee and leader of 
the Bani Tamim tribe. It added that he was found dead in his 
apartment in Beirut the day before yesterday. FIC sources say 
that early information indicates that Iraqi Government organs 
were behind the assassination operation. In a statement, a copy 
of which AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has received, the council said an 
armed group stormed Talib Suhayl's apartment and shot him. 
  The council pointed out that the dead man had on several 
occasions told his family and FIC Chairman Sa'd Salih Jabr about 
telephone murder threats he had received in recent months from 
elements belonging to the regime of Iraqi President Saddam 
Husayn. 
  The statement, signed by Sa'd Salih Jabr, said that Talib 
Suhayl was forced to leave Amman, his permanent residence, as a 
result of these threats. He moved between a number of capitals, 
the latest was Beirut. [passage omitted] 
  Elsewhere, the support office of the Supreme Assembly of the 
Islamic Revolution in Iraq issued a statement yesterday in which 
it cited strong rumors about President Saddam Husayn's health. 
Dr. Hamid al-Bayyati, FIC representative in London, said that 
circles close to the authorities (in Baghdad) leaked information 
about Saddam's suffering from a serious illness as a result of 
which he is confined to bed, and that a team of doctors are 
supervising his treatment for hysterical nervous fits following 
which he goes into a coma for many hours. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

