<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Meets Italian Deputies, Notes Business Prospects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Meets Italian Deputies, Notes Business Prospects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1304175294 Baghdad INA in Arabic 1410 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN1304175294 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, 13 Apr (INA)--Ahmad Murtada Ahmad, minister 
of transportation and communications, has stressed Iraq's 
readiness to discuss and study the signing and implementation of 
contracts with Italian firms and institutions in the fields of 
transportation and communications. 
  During a meeting today with Italian members of parliament 
Antonio Catika and Joseph Sarta [names as received], the 
minister said that such contracts would include railroads, 
communications, aviation, airlines, maritime transportation, 
trucks, and buses, and could be worth billions of dollars. 
  He said Italian firms had benefited from the extensive 
commercial ties that once existed between Iraq and Italy. He 
said such firms suffered grave losses as a result of the unfair 
embargo imposed on Iraq by the U.S. Administration. 
  The two Italian parliament members stressed that they will 
brief the Italian parliament during its next session on their 
impressions of the situation in Iraq and the suffering of the 
Iraqi people as a result of the blockade. They will also brief 
the Italian parliament on the extensive business prospects 
available for Italian firms in Iraq. 

</TEXT>

