<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yemeni Reform Grouping Threatened With `Isolation' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yemeni Reform Grouping Threatened With `Isolation' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1304144094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 13 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1304144094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hamud Munsir: "Danger of Tribal Dispute and </F>
Political Isolation Threaten Yemeni Reform Grouping"] 
  [Text] Sanaa -- The Yemeni Reform Grouping [YRG] -- the 
third partner in the ruling coalition in Sanaa -- is faced with 
two problems: One at the tribal level, namely with the main 
tendency in its formation, and another at the political level. 
The two problems threaten to reduce its role in power in the 
future as a result of the tribal dispute between the Hashid 
tribe, from which the grouping's leadership comes, and the Bakil 
tribe. And also because of the external moves and bilateral 
contacts between its partners in power: The General People's 
Congress [GPC] and the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP]. [passage 
omitted) 
  Corroborated information obtained by AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT says 
that the Nasirite Unionist Party -- an opposition party -- has 
not yet decided to open a dialogue with the YRG, because the 
latter is a partner in government. Meanwhile the YRG feels 
isolated because of its exclusion from many of the consultations 
inside the ruling coalition, especially after the YSP sensed 
some contradictions between the GPC and the Reform Grouping and 
thus began to exploit them. 
  However, observers point to a kind of breakthrough toward a 
solution to the crisis in the light of the mediation efforts 
made by Egypt and the United Arab Emirates. They expect a 
meeting to be held between President Salih and Vice President 
al-Bid in Cairo at the beginning of next month at the latest to 
restore stability to Yemen before the unity anniversary on 22 
May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

