<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Bashir Criticizes Garang's Visit to Israel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Bashir Criticizes Garang's Visit to Israel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA1304192594 Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network in 
Arabic 1300 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1304192594 </F>
<F P=104>  Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lieutenant General 'Umar al-Bashir, the president of 
the Republic, has stressed that rebel John Garang's recent visit 
to Israel was made after the failure of the self-determination 
proposal put forward by the rebel movement and its failure to 
internationalize the problem of the south. This was also 
accompanied by the routing of its forces. 
  Speaking today during his meeting with media leaders at the 
secretariat general of the Council of Ministers building, Lt. 
Gen. al-Bashir said it had been confirmed that Israel and the 
Zionist lobby were promoting an anti-Sudan media campaign in the 
West and that Israel was using Garang as one of its tools with 
which to fight the Sudanese Government. The president of the 
Republic referred to the symposium organized by a number of 
well-known leftist movements in Cairo to be held on 14 May which 
is just two days before the resumption of negotiations between 
the Sudanese Government and the rebel movement in Nairobi. He 
said the organizers of this symposium had invited John Garang 
and Riak Machar to attend. 
  During his meeting, Lt. Gen. al-Bashir stressed that the 
Western world was trying to stir up discord in Africa, referring 
in this context to the Israeli enemy's aim to gain control of 
the sources of the Nile in the African continent with their 
water resources, in order to put pressure on the main forces in 
the region. The president of the Republic stressed the need for 
the Africans to take the initiative to solve disputes within the 
continent so as to preserve its security and stability. 
  Lt. Gen. al-Bashir declared that the rebel movement's 
refusal 
to sign the relief agreement with the government revealed that 
the movement secretly intended to obstruct relief efforts in 
order to prepare the way for foreign intervention in Sudan. His 
excellency reiterated the Sudanese Government's determination to 
ensure that relief operations were successful. 

</TEXT>

