<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Threats' To Boycott Peace Talks Taken Seriously </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Threats' To Boycott Peace Talks Taken Seriously </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1304141294 Amman AL-BILAD in Arabic 13 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN1304141294 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-BILAD </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On the eve of the 20 April visit to the United 
States by His Royal Highness Prince Hasan, AL-BILAD has learned 
from reliable sources in Washington that the U.S. Administration 
is taking Jordanian threats to boycott the talks seriously. 
AL-BILAD has learned that the United States will agree, during 
their meeting with Prince Hasan, to the inspection of 
al-'Aqabah-bound ships inside the port by Lloyds, not the U.S. 
Navy. AL-BILAD has also learned that the resumption of the 
[Arab-Israeli] talks and the expansion of participation in the 
multilateral talks will be raised by the United States during 
the talks. 
  Meanwhile, Jordanian officials say that holding the talks 
the 
way the Israelis want is rejected by the Jordanians, because 
this is intended to bypass the agenda in order to postpone 
priority issues. Furthermore, the Israeli request to sign a 
peace treaty with Jordan before discussing substantial issues, 
such as borders, refugees, and water, is considered impossible 
by the Jordanian leadership. This, consequently, will not make 
Prince Hasan's U.S. visit at all easy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

