<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shaykh Yamani Predicts Iraqi Return to Oil Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shaykh Yamani Predicts Iraqi Return to Oil Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1304103294 London AL-QUDS AL-'ARABI in Arabic 12 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM1304103294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-QUDS AL-'ARABI </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Yamani: Iraq Returns to Oil Market </F>
Next Year"] 
  [Text] London, AL-QUDS AL-'ARABI -- Former Saudi Oil 
Minister Shaykh Ahmad Zaki Yamani told an oil conference in 
London yesterday that there are indications that a number of 
Security Council members have become more agreeable to Iraq's 
returning to the world oil market, and that it can be assumed 
that this will happen in the middle of next year. 
  In his opening speech to the fourth conference of the World 
Energy Studies Center, which he heads, Yamani said that Iraq's 
resumption of oil exports would put OPEC members under great 
pressure unless they work to offer it a suitable quota of the 
organization's output. He added that the oil price would in 
this case fall to $10 a barrel and remain at this level during 
1996. 
  Yamani pointed out that the official U.S. position on Iraq's 
resuming its oil exports continues to make it conditional on 
Iraq's compliance with all UN resolutions concerning Iraq, but 
this position is not now as clear as it used to be. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

