<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak-Yeltsin Summit Scheduled for May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mubarak-Yeltsin Summit Scheduled for May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1304135894 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 13 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM1304135894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "First Egyptian-Russian Summit in Five </F>
Years"] 
  [Text] Cairo, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- Cairo will in May 
witness the first Egyptian-Russian summit meeting in over five 
years. Russian President Boris Yeltsin will visit Egypt during a 
tour of the Middle East which will take him also to Syria, 
Jordan, and Israel. 
  Reliable political sources in Cairo have told AL-SHARQ 
AL-AWSAT that the peace process in the Middle East will be high 
on the agenda of the first summit meeting between Egyptian 
President Husni Mubarak and Russian President Yeltsin. A round 
of talks confined to the two leaders will be held before the two 
delegations join the talks. Egyptian Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
and Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev will participate in 
the talks. 
  The sources confirmed that the Egyptian-Russian talks will 
discuss in their political and economic aspects ways of 
reinforcing bilateral relations in the various spheres and the 
two countries' contribution to advancing the Arab-Israeli peace 
negotiations, in addition to reviewing two countries' efforts in 
this connection. 
  The discussions will also include the possibility of 
settling 
some of the outstanding issues with regard to payment methods in 
the economic and trade exchange and agreeing on the preparation 
of a new trade exchange protocol guaranteeing an increase in the 
volume of trade exchange between them on the basis of new terms 
by closing the file concerning the settlement of payments 
related to the former Soviet Union. 
  The sources pointed out that Yeltsin's Middle East tour 
reflects a Russian desire to regain the active role to achieve a 
peace based on justice and accentuate Russia's commitment to the 
need to guarantee the legitimate Arab rights to territory and 
peace. 
  AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned from political sources that 
Yeltsin and his foreign minister are expected to discuss with 
leaders of the states they are going to visit a number of 
Russian proposals and initiatives that will reflect positively 
on the Arab-Israeli peace negotiations. And that the Russian 
talks in Israel will deal primarily with settling the 
Arab-Israeli conflict in a comprehensive manner that is fair to 
all parties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

