<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rao: Any Restriction on Nuclear Option `Unacceptable' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rao: Any Restriction on Nuclear Option `Unacceptable' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1304161394 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1304161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The prime minister says any suggestion to restrict 
the country's nuclear option is unacceptable in view of 
Pakistan's acquisition of nuclear capabilities. Addressing the 
Army Commanders Conference in New Delhi today, Mr. Narasimha Rao 
said India is in favor of a time-bound universal and 
nondiscriminatory nuclear disarmament. He said New Delhi has 
always advocated peaceful uses of nuclear energy. Referring to 
the allegations of human rights violations, he said that 
anti-India forces are using these for political exploitation. 
Mr. Rao called upon such forces to stop maligning India on this 
score as New Delhi's concern for human rights is second to none. 
The prime minister said that the low intensity conflict 
sponsored by Pakistan in Jammu and Kashmir is a major challenge. 
Islamabad is sending terrorists, including foreign mercenaries, 
to the state, he added. 

</TEXT>

